                        Status Badges</a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-200 mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">üß© Sample Component: AdminStatCardExample</h2>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
                <code class="text-[11px]">AdminStatCardExample</code> shows how to render the same stat card component
                three different ways: for MRR, active subscriptions, and churn. Each card uses a shared layout but
                different labels, values, and status badges.
            </p>

            <div class="bg-gray-100 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto mb-4">
                <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-1">Components/Pages/Examples/Admin/Step2/AdminStatCardExample.razor
                </div>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mb-2">Razor markup that uses a single stat card component multiple times
                    with different parameters.</p>
                <ul class="list-disc ml-4 mb-3 text-[11px] text-gray-600 space-y-1">
                    <li>Shows how to pass title, value, helper text, and status into a reusable component.</li>
                    <li>Uses small color differences to indicate "good", "neutral", and "warning" states.</li>
                    <li>Lays the foundation for the tiles that will appear at the top of <code
                            class="text-[11px]">/admin/dashboard</code>.</li>
                </ul>
                <pre data-code-title="Razor (AdminStatCardExample.razor)"
                    class="code-block text-xs sm:text-sm font-mono text-gray-800 w-full max-w-full overflow-x-auto">@@page &quot;/admin-examples/demo-stat-cards&quot;
@@rendermode InteractiveServer
@@inherits AdminStatCardExampleBase

&lt;h3 class=&quot;text-xl font-semibold mb-3&quot;&gt;Admin Stat Cards Demo&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;div class=&quot;grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3&quot;&gt;
    &lt;AdminStatCard
        Title=&quot;Monthly Recurring Revenue&quot;
        Value=&quot;$24,800&quot;
        HelperText=&quot;+8.2% vs last month&quot;
        Status=&quot;good&quot; /&gt;

    &lt;AdminStatCard
        Title=&quot;Active Subscriptions&quot;
        Value=&quot;1,204&quot;
        HelperText=&quot;Starter, Growth, and Scale plans&quot;
        Status=&quot;neutral&quot; /&gt;

    &lt;AdminStatCard
        Title=&quot;Churn This Month&quot;
        Value=&quot;2.1%&quot;
        HelperText=&quot;Watching accounts at risk closely&quot;
        Status=&quot;warning&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</pre>
            </div>

            <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-2">Step-by-step breakdown</h3>
            <div class="grid gap-4">
                <div class="bg-gray-100 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-1">1. Define a stat card API</div>
                    <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mb-2">Start by giving your stat card a clear set of parameters so it
                        can represent any metric, not just MRR.</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-4 mb-2 text-[11px] text-gray-600 space-y-1">
                        <li>Keep parameter names simple: <code class="text-[11px]">Title</code>, <code
                                class="text-[11px]">Value</code>, <code class="text-[11px]">HelperText</code>, and <code
                                class="text-[11px]">Status</code>.</li>
                        <li>Use <code class="text-[11px]">Status</code> to pick colors (good, neutral, warning).</li>
                        <li>Avoid hard-coding numbers so you can reuse the card in other steps.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <pre
                        class="code-block text-xs sm:text-sm font-mono text-gray-800 w-full max-w-full overflow-x-auto">[Parameter] public string Title { get; set; } = string.Empty;
[Parameter] public string Value { get; set; } = string.Empty;
[Parameter] public string HelperText { get; set; } = string.Empty;
[Parameter] public string Status { get; set; } = &quot;neutral&quot;;</pre>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-gray-100 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-1">2. Map status to semantic styles</div>
                    <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mb-2">Use a small helper method to translate the <code
                            class="text-[11px]">Status</code> into Tailwind-style utility classes so your UI stays
                        consistent.</p>
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-4 mb-2 text-[11px] text-gray-600 space-y-1">
                        <li>Return a different text color for good/neutral/warning states.</li>
                        <li>Keep the mapping logic in one place so you can tweak it later.</li>
                        <li>Reuse the same pattern in later steps for badges and lock states.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <pre
                        class="code-block text-xs sm:text-sm font-mono text-gray-800 w-full max-w-full overflow-x-auto">protected string GetStatusTextClass() =&gt; Status switch
{
    &quot;good&quot; =&gt; &quot;text-emerald-600&quot;,
    &quot;warning&quot; =&gt; &quot;text-amber-600&quot;,
    _ =&gt; &quot;text-slate-600&quot;
};</pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-6 border border-gray-200 mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">üìù Important Notes &amp; Tips</h2>
            <div class="space-y-3">
                <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-blue-900 mb-3">üí° Pro Tips</h3>
                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div>
                            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Design once, reuse everywhere</p>
                            <p class="text-xs text-blue-800">Treat this stat card like a mini design system component.
                                Once you dial in the spacing and typography, you can reuse it in Step 3 and on the real
                                <code class="text-[11px]">/admin/dashboard</code> page.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Keep content and layout separate</p>
                            <p class="text-xs text-blue-800">Passing values in via parameters keeps your Razor markup
                                clean and lets you swap out metrics without touching the component layout.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 rounded-lg p-4">
                    <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-yellow-900 mb-2">‚ö†Ô∏è Troubleshooting</h3>
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-sm text-yellow-900 space-y-1">
                        <li>If the cards all look the same, double-check you're passing different <code
                                class="text-[11px]">Title</code>, <code class="text-[11px]">Value</code>, and <code
                                class="text-[11px]">Status</code> values.</li>
                        <li>If the status colors never change, confirm your helper uses the exact status strings you're
                            passing in.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-100 to-purple-100 rounded-xl p-6 mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">üõ†Ô∏è How to do it</h2>
            <ol class="list-decimal ml-5 space-y-2 text-gray-700">
                <li>
                    <strong>Create the demo component:</strong>
                    Add <code>AdminStatCardExample.razor</code> and <code>AdminStatCardExample.razor.cs</code> under
                    <code>Components/Pages/Examples/Admin/Step2</code>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Build the reusable card:</strong>
                    Implement an <code>AdminStatCard</code> component in the same folder that accepts parameters for
                    label, value, helper text, and status.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Render multiple metrics:</strong>
                    Use the card three times in the demo to show different admin metrics and verify the layout still
                    feels balanced.
                </li>
            </ol>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-black/3 rounded-2xl p-6 mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">üé¨ Live Demo</h2>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">Use the demo below to see how a single stat card component can
                represent different admin metrics just by changing its parameters.</p>
            <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl border border-gray-200 p-6">
                <AdminStatCardExample />
